<h3 class="heading"><span class="type">Paragraph</span></h3>
<p>Recall that earlier in this section we encountered the integral</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p class="continuation">in trying to determine the solution to the catenary.  We actually have the tools to solve this type of integral once we notice that (surprisingly!) we would like to use the substitution <span class="process-math">\(z=\tan(\theta)\text{.}\)</span>  As strange as it sounds to take a perfectly good integral and purposely insert trigonometry into it, this is just the ticket here.  Since we have the trigonometric identity  <span class="process-math">\(\tan^2(\theta)+1=\sec^2(\theta)\)</span> then this substitution is just the thing to rid us of the square root, which poses more of an issue than the trigonometryffff does.  Specifically, if we let <span class="process-math">\(z=\tan(\theta)\)</span> , then <span class="process-math">\(\dx{z}=
\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta{}}\text{,}\)</span> and so we have</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}=\int\frac{\sec^2(\theta)}{\sqrt{1+\tan^2(\theta{})}}\dx{z}=\int\frac{\sec^2(\theta)}{\sec(\theta){}}\dx{\theta{}}=\int\sec(\theta)\dx{\theta{}}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<span class="incontext"><a href="section-6.html#p-113" class="internal">in-context</a></span>
</body>
